  {
    "url": "https://www.tiktok.com/@sararitaplans/video/7653513052918156558",
    "post_id": "7653513052918156558",
    "description": "a perfect way to explore alfama #lisbonportugal #travelitinerary #lisbontravel #travelguide #portugaltravel  mapped 4 days Lisbon itinerary  what to do in Lisbon things to do in alfama  perfect day in Lisbon\nFollow a relaxed Day 1 in Alfama: São Jorge Castle, pastel de nata at António, Miradouro de Santa Luzia, Feira da Ladra, lunch in Alfama and sunset at the miradouro. #lisbonportugal #travelguide\nLead\nA relaxed first day in Lisbon focused on Alfama gives you the feel of the city without turning sightseeing into a checklist. This guide follows the video’s route: start at São Jorge Castle, enjoy local pastry and coffee, visit two miradouros (viewpoints), browse Feira da Ladra when available, wander Alfama’s streets, and finish with dinner and sunset near the cathedral.\n\nMorning — São Jorge Castle and a pastel de nata\nBegin at São Jorge Castle to take in sweeping views over Lisbon. From the castle, stroll down a street filled with local shops and stop at António for your first pastel de nata. The video highlights António’s version as “not too sweet” — pair it with a cup of coffee and take your time to soak in the neighborhood.\n\nMid-morning — Miradouros and photos\nWalk toward the riverside and visit Miradouro de Santa Luzia and Miradouro das Portas do Sol. Both are iconic viewpoints in Alfama. They can be busier later in the day, but photos taken now are less likely to be backlogged. Enjoy the tile-lined benches, rooftops, and river views.\n\nOptional detour — Feira da Ladra (Tuesdays and Saturdays)\nIf your visit falls on a Tuesday or Saturday, make a quick detour to Feira da Ladra, Lisbon’s flea market. The video recommends it for cool trinkets and an indoor market with goods from local artisans. It’s a short walk from the miradouros and worth a browse before continuing your route.\n\nLunchtime — Wander Alfama’s alleys\nReturn to Alfama’s middle section and drift through tight streets and alleyways. This area is ideal for lunch; the video mentions Casa São Miguel as a whimsical spot (note: the pastel there wasn’t tried in the clip). Choose a small local restaurant to sample traditional dishes and continue enjoying the neighborhood atmosphere.\n\nAfternoon — Drift toward Praça do Comércio\nAfter lunch, the suggested plan is to drift from Alfama down toward Praça do Comércio. Let the streets guide you rather than forcing a strict schedule — the point is a relaxed exploration that captures Alfama’s character.\n\nEvening — Dinner by the cathedral and sunset\nHave dinner near Lisbon Cathedral. Afterward, head back up to one of the miradouros for an iconic sunset over the city and river. This finishes Day 1 on a classic Lisbon note: food, views, and historic streets.\n\nClose / Takeaway\nThis Day 1 itinerary emphasizes a slow, enjoyable pace in Alfama: São Jorge Castle, pastel de nata at António, Santa Luzia and Portas do Sol viewpoints, Feira da Ladra on market days, wandering for lunch, and a sunset by the miradouro after dinner near the cathedral. Does this relaxed route match how you like to explore cities, or would you add specific museums or tram rides? \n\nidentified_languages",
